First, the right hand side of an `{if ` block is treated as a string literal.

So `{if code1_check == code1` checks if the attribute named <code style="border: 1px solid grey">code1_check </code> (the space is treated as part of the attribute name) is equal to the string <code style="border: 1px solid grey">= code1</code>.
The second checks if the attribute named `{code1_check}`  is different from the string <code style="border: 1px solid grey">{code1}</code>.

If you want to compare two attributes, you need to use the `@` prefix. I think what you want in this case is:

```
{if code1_check=@code1:Great}
{if code1_check<>@code1:Great_no}   
```
Or, as you're checking two sides of one condition, you could do:
```
{if code1_check=@code1:Great}
{else:Great_no}   
```
